💡 Key Point from your image: Traffic from users goes through the Route Table first, then hits the Gateway Load Balancer, which sends it to the Target Group of 3rd Party Security Virtual Appliances before it reaches the actual application. The application never receives uninspected traffic.

🔍 What Are 3rd Party Security Virtual Appliances?
Table


Appliance	Purpose
Firewall	Block/allow traffic based on rules
IDS (Intrusion Detection System)	Detect suspicious/malicious traffic
IPS (Intrusion Prevention System)	Detect AND block malicious traffic
Deep Packet Inspection (DPI)	Inspect packet content for threats
Web Application Firewall (WAF)	Protect against web-based attacks
Examples: Palo Alto Networks, Fortinet, Check Point, Cisco — all can run as virtual appliances behind a GLB.

⚙️ How GLB Works Technically:
Protocol Used: GENEVE (port 6081)

Step 1 — Traffic arrives from internet/user
         │
         ▼
Step 2 — Route Table redirects traffic to GLB endpoint
         │
         ▼
Step 3 — GLB encapsulates packets using GENEVE protocol
         and sends to security appliances (Target Group)
         │
         ▼
Step 4 — Security appliance inspects the packet:
         ├── Malicious? → Drop it ❌
         └── Safe?      → Return to GLB ✅
         │
         ▼
Step 5 — GLB forwards approved traffic to Application
